{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658459"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20750"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79405"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11717"},{"type":"tags","id":"12615"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32767"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EViral haemorrhagic fevers are severe systemic diseases characterised by widespread vascular damage, haemorrhage, and shock. These diseases are caused by several families of RNA viruses that typically circulate in animal reservoirs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathogenesis of viral haemorrhagic fever?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct viral infection of endothelial cells or cytokine-mediated damage","Immune complex deposition in vessel walls leading to complement activation and inflammation","Antibody-dependent enhancement of infection with subsequent massive cytokine release","Complement-mediated destruction of platelets resulting in severe thrombocytopaenia","Bacterial endotoxin release"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathogenesis of viral haemorrhagic fever involves \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect viral infection of endothelial cells or cytokine-mediated damage\u003C/strong\u003E. The viruses can directly infect and damage endothelial cells, or they can infect macrophages and dendritic cells, leading to production of inflammatory cytokines that damage blood vessels. This vascular damage is a key feature of the disease and leads to the characteristic haemorrhage and shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune complex deposition in vessel walls leading to complement activation and inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - While immune complexes can cause vasculitis in some conditions, this is not the primary mechanism in viral haemorrhagic fevers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibody-dependent enhancement of infection with subsequent massive cytokine release\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is more relevant to diseases like dengue fever when a person is infected with a second serotype, but is not the primary pathogenic mechanism of viral haemorrhagic fevers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement-mediated destruction of platelets resulting in severe thrombocytopaenia\u003C/strong\u003E - Although thrombocytopaenia occurs in viral haemorrhagic fevers, it is not primarily due to complement-mediated platelet destruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial endotoxin release\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral haemorrhagic fevers are caused by RNA viruses, not bacteria or bacterial toxins\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EViral haemorrhagic fevers are caused by enveloped RNA viruses from four genera: \u003Cem\u003EArenaviridae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EFiloviridae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EBunyaviridae\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EFlaviviridae\u003C/em\u003E. Humans are incidental hosts who become infected through contact with infected animal hosts (typically rodents) or insect vectors (mosquitoes and ticks). Some viruses, such as Ebola, Marburg, and Lassa, can also spread from person to person.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Viral haemorrhagic fevers are caused by enveloped RNA viruses from four genera: Arenaviridae, Filoviridae, Bunyaviridae, and Flaviviridae.","The pathogenesis of viral haemorrhagic fevers involves vascular damage leading to widespread haemorrhage and shock.","Humans are incidental hosts who become infected through contact with animal hosts or insect vectors.","Some viral haemorrhagic fevers (Ebola, Marburg, Lassa) can spread from person to person."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 352."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79405"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79405"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:04:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:06:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96790"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":